'''Princess Tachibana no Nakatsu''' (? – fl. 539) was {{ill|Empress of Japan|en|Empress of Japan|WD=Q595038|lt=Empress of Japan|1=Empress of Japan}} as the consort of {{ill|Emperor Senka|en|Emperor Senka|WD=Q329728|lt=Emperor Senka|1=Emperor Senka}}.<ref> Anston, W.G. (1896). Transactions and Proceedings of The Japan Society, London. Supplement I. Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697. Vol. 1. London: Kegan Paul, Trench, Trüber, & Co.</ref> She gave birth to five children. Tachibana no Nakatsu was the daughter of {{ill|Emperor Ninken|en|Emperor Ninken|WD=Q357266|lt=Emperor Ninken|1=Emperor Ninken}} and {{ill|Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume|en|Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume|WD=Q11088800|lt=Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume|1=Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume}}. She became empress dowager from 539.

'''Tachibana no Naka no Ōkimi''' (橘仲皇女, birth and death dates unknown) was the {{ill|Empress|ja|皇后|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Empress consort|WD=Q7723211}} of {{ill|Emperor Senka|en|Emperor Senka|WD=Q329728|lt=Emperor Senka|1=Emperor Senka}}. In the {{ill|Kojiki|en|Kojiki|WD=Q813031|lt=Kojiki|1=Kojiki}}, she is referred to as Tachibana no Naka no Hime no Mikoto (橘之中比売命). Her father was {{ill|Emperor Ninken|en|Emperor Ninken|WD=Q357266|lt=Emperor Ninken|1=Emperor Ninken}}, and her mother was {{ill|Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume|en|Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume|WD=Q11088800|lt=Kasuga no Ōiratsume no Ōkimi|1=Princess Kasuga no Ōiratsume}}, the {{ill|Princess|en|Princess|WD=Q863048|lt=Princess|1=Princess}} of {{ill|Emperor Yūryaku|en|Emperor Yūryaku|WD=Q357235|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|1=Emperor Yūryaku}}. She was the mother of {{ill|Princess Ishi-hime|en|Princess Ishi-hime|WD=Q11585498|lt=Princess Ishi|1=Princess Ishi-hime}} (Empress of {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|en|Emperor Kinmei|WD=Q329792|lt=Emperor Kinmei|1=Emperor Kinmei}}).

She was enthroned as the Empress of Emperor Senka on {{ill|March 8 (old calendar)|ja|3月8日 (旧暦)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/March 8 (old calendar)|1=March 8 (Lunisolar)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q838873}} in the first year of his reign ({{ill|April 14, 536|ja|536年4月14日|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/April 14, 536|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}). After her death, she was interred alongside Emperor Senka and their young children in the same {{ill|tomb|ja|陵|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tomb|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 宮内庁治定陵墓の一覧|1=Q28686274|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q28686274}}. The only other Empresses known to have been interred with their Emperors are {{ill|Princess Kasuga no Yamada|en|Princess Kasuga no Yamada|WD=Q11088803|lt=Princess Kasuga no Yamada|1=Princess Kasuga no Yamada}} (Empress of {{ill|Emperor Ankan|en|Emperor Ankan|WD=Q241765|lt=Emperor Ankan|1=Emperor Ankan}}, according to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|en|Nihon Shoki|WD=Q813935|lt=Nihon Shoki|1=Nihon Shoki}}, although the current official designation is different) and {{ill|Empress Jitō|en|Empress Jitō|WD=Q232026|lt=Empress Jitō|1=Empress Jitō}} (Empress of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|2=ja|3=天武天皇|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|2=ja|3=天武天皇|1=Emperor Tenmu|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q335181}}).

